From: andreas@orion.mgen.uni-heidelberg.de ()
Subject: Re: This is Not a Question.  (Is it?)
Date: Mon, 18 Oct 93 23:38:44 GMT

David S. Fox (fox@graphics.cs.nyu.edu) wrote:
: It is unreasonable to exclude all questions from any newsgroup,
: since questions arise as a result of almost any linguistic 
: interaction.  What we need to do is distinguish between the
: types of questions we are trying to direct to comp.os.linux.help
: and the sorts of questions acceptable everywhere.  For example,
: questions starting "How do I...?" usually belong in the help
: group, but "How should we (re-design the schedular to eliminate
: thrashing when running out of swap space)?" or "What do you think
: of this idea (for re-designing the scheduler...)?" should be
: acceptable in the development group.  Questions like "Do you
: want me to (distribute my PCMCIA drivers)?" are acceptable anywhere.
: My point is that the directive "Please don't post questions here"
: is absurd.  These postings need to be re-thought and re-written.
: --
: -david --  fox@graphics.cs.nyu.edu

It might be the better idea to redirect the answers, either by not
answering at all to the wrong type of question or by posting the 
answer to c.o.l.h. You will never be able to prevent all misdirected
questions, but the chances might be a little bit better with directing
the answers. And if only the questions appear and not the followups and
flames (which in general should go via email, I do not like to wast my
time with skipping flames for misdirected questions) then the amount of 
inappropriate posts could be drastically reduced.
And it might even be that more people begin to think that c.o.l.h is
the right place to put their question.

Andreas

--

Andreas Helke

Institut fuer molekulare Genetik, Universitaet Heidelberg
Im Neuenheimer Feld 230 
69122 Heidelberg

