From: camerons@NAD.3Com.COM (Cameron Spitzer)
Crossposted-To: comp.sys.ibm.pc.hardware,comp.sys.ibm.pc.misc
Subject: CMS Jumbo 250-Linux status (was Re: Advice & Ref Books for 486 based PC?)
Date: 19 Oct 93 00:42:56 GMT
Reply-To: cls@truffula.sj.ca.us


Last Friday, I warned (in comp.sys.ibm.pc.hardware) against the
CMS Jumbo 250 for non-DOS (ie. Linux) applications.  I was, it
seems, out of date.
Let this article serve as a correction and an update.
Sorry if you see the quoted articles twice.

In article 2155@bridge2.NSD.3Com.COM, I wrote:
>In article 23721@berlioz.nsc.com, scharf@mirage.nsc.com
 (Steven M. Scharf) writes:

>>Get a Colorado Jumbo 250MB floppy controller based tape unit. 
>
>Again, beware if you intend to run anything but MSDOS-Windows.
>Check your intended OS's docs to see if there's a working
>driver for any peripheral that goes on a floppy cable or
>parallel port.


When I got home (where I do most of my Usenetting) I found
two articles about CMS and Linux in comp.os.linux.development.

In <CEuuvI.Bqt@cbnewsk.cb.att.com>, Steve Falco
(saf@whservh.att.com) reported trouble with his CMS Jumbo 250:

>I had a CMS Jumbo 250 tape drive which worked when used with DOS (mostly).
>It was a pain to spend 2 hours formatting a tape but it was cheap.  Then
>I bought ESIX 4.0.4 and found that the CMS drive was not really
>QIC-40/80 compatible.  At least it wouldn't work with either of the ESIX
>drivers.  So I bought the SYSV driver from CMS.
 
>Sometimes it would work.  Other times I would get kernel panics.  Other
>times a tape would simply fail to read back.  I even sent a tape that
>would not format back to 3M - they tested the tape, said it was fine,
>and that the drive was at fault.
 
>I gave up on CMS and went to an Archive SCSI drive.  It has been 100%
>reliable for DOS, ESIX, and Linux.  No more time wasted formatting
>tapes, and I can simultaneously use the floppies while using the tape
>drive.  I know it costs more, but if ever there was a case where you
>get what you pay for, this is it.  I recommend avoiding CMS drives.


But Gareth Bult (gareth@gblinux.demon.co.uk) in <392@gblinux.demon.co.uk>
gave a promising status report on his success with the new Linux driver
for the thing:

>I have now downloaded the real driver along with the new version of modules.
>This now seems to work quite well with pl13. Indeed I just removed all the
>tracing and comments and managed to do a full backup of my root fs.
>
>Stats: 486/33DX with 16Mb using CMS Jumbo 250 with DC2120:
>Data Volume:  127.5Mb                     Time Taken:   43:53
[...]
>Effecive DTR: around 3Mb/minute.
>              ...This agrees with the figures listed in the spec...
>              ...It rekons about 3Mb/min also...
[...]
>While backing up, I put a SLIP connection up to internet.. I still got
>GOOD throughput on a NEWS download with no apparent ill effect on the tape
>drive... so timing/interrupt wise the driver seems great.
>
>In general the source (and performance) of the driver is pretty impressive.
>Hence, I see no point in continuing with my driver.
>--I can tar to/from the drive, but have done none of the bad sector/ecc
>work.
[...]
>There seem to be only a few outstanding points from what I've seen & heard;
>1) Ability to switch on/off hardware compression
>2) More testing of ecc/bad sector handling
>   --I saw 2 ecc messages I wasn't too sure of
>3) Size could do with reducing
>4) De-module it and send it to Linus for pl14...


Cameron in Santa Clara


------------------------------

From: rgg@aaii.oz.au (Rupert G. Goldie)
Subject: Re: Is there a better vi?
Date: Tue, 19 Oct 1993 00:42:41 GMT

rpao@mts.mivj.ca.us (Roger C. Pao) writes:

>It's nice that Linux comes with vi, but it is a subset.  I can't do real
>vi operations like Ctrl-Shift-^ to switch between the last two files.
>I can't do a colon operation like ":123,s/tic/tac/g" and expect it to
>substitute all occurrances of tic for tac starting from line 123 to where
>the cursor is currently.
>So, anyone have a vi which is really vi compatible?

I use vile which is mostly vi compatible (:map support is weak, but being 
worked on), but has the added advantage of providing multiple buffers 
(pulled from microemacs). You can get the source from ftp.cayman.com:/pub/vile/
or a binary from sunsite.unc.edu:/pub/Linux/apps/editors/vile-3.61-bin.tar.gz

Rupert
--
Rupert G. Goldie, Research Scientist                rgg@aaii.oz.au
Australian Artificial Intelligence Institute        
/\/\|| 1 Grattan Street, Melbourne, Australia

